hands_on_practices.solution:
The molar conversion efficiency is defined as the fraction of the final DCA moles among the total final moles of CA and DCA. Denote $m_{\mathrm{CA}},m_{\mathrm{DCA}}$ as the measured masses and $M_{\mathrm{CA}},M_{\mathrm{DCA}}$ as molar masses. Using $n = m/M$, the efficiency is
$$
\eta = \frac{n_{\mathrm{DCA}}}{n_{\mathrm{CA}} + n_{\mathrm{DCA}}}
= \frac{\frac{m_{\mathrm{DCA}}}{M_{\mathrm{DCA}}}}{\frac{m_{\mathrm{CA}}}{M_{\mathrm{CA}}} + \frac{m_{\mathrm{DCA}}}{M_{\mathrm{DCA}}}}
= \frac{m_{\mathrm{DCA}} M_{\mathrm{CA}}}{m_{\mathrm{DCA}} M_{\mathrm{CA}} + m_{\mathrm{CA}} M_{\mathrm{DCA}}}.
$$
For Group B, $m_{\mathrm{CA}} = 1.25\ \mathrm{mg}$, $m_{\mathrm{DCA}} = 1.80\ \mathrm{mg}$, $M_{\mathrm{CA}} = 408.6\ \mathrm{g/mol}$, and $M_{\mathrm{DCA}} = 392.6\ \mathrm{g/mol}$. Substituting,
$$
\eta = \frac{(1.80)(408.6)}{(1.80)(408.6) + (1.25)(392.6)} 
= \frac{735.48}{735.48 + 490.75}
= \frac{735.48}{1226.23}
\approx 0.599789.
$$
Rounding to three significant figures gives $0.600$.
